data.content:
Three EF Core 10 breaking changes hit your code directly:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your entire expression-tree construction block no longer compiles. Replace it with:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No more `Expression.Lambda`, `Expression.Call`, or `Expression.Parameter` — just normal C# control flow inside the lambda.

---

### 2. Complex type column names are now uniquified/use full paths

Two sub-changes:

- **Duplicate property names across complex types** (e.g. `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street`) — columns get a numeric suffix to uniquify them. A migration will rename columns.
- **Nested complex types** use the full path: `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` now maps to `Payment_BillingAddress_City` (was `BillingAddress_City`).

**Fix:** Pin the old names explicitly to avoid a migration renaming columns:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress, sa =>
        sa.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress, ba =>
        ba.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street"));
});

// For nested complex types — preserve old column name:
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment, p =>
        p.ComplexProperty(pay => pay.BillingAddress, ba =>
            ba.Property(a => a.City).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City")));
});
```

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) gained a `string logCommandText` parameter. Your implementation won't compile until you add it:

```csharp
public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
    IRelationalConnection connection, DbCommand command,
    DbContext context, Guid commandId, Guid connectionId,
    DateTimeOffset startTime,
    string logCommandText)   // ← new: redacted SQL safe for logging
{ /* logging — use logCommandText instead of command.CommandText for logs */ }
```

`logCommandText` contains SQL with constants redacted; use it for logging. Use `command.CommandText` when you need the actual SQL.
